  "prompt": "What is the risk side for giving antivenom to envenomated people?",
  "response": "Giving antivenom to envenomated patients carries several potential risks:\n\n1. Allergic Reactions\n- Immediate hypersensitivity reactions\n- Anaphylaxis\n- Potential for severe systemic allergic response\n- Risk increases with previous exposure to antivenom\n\n2. Serum Sickness\n- Delayed immunological response\n- Can occur 7-14 days after administration\n- Symptoms include fever, rash, joint pain\n- Result of immune complex formation\n\n3. Immunological Complications\n- Potential immune system overreaction\n- Potential development of antibodies\n- Risk of future immune response complications\n\n4. Specific Reaction Risks\n- Depends on antivenom type and specific snake species\n- Potential cross-reactivity between antivenoms\n- Variation in individual patient sensitivity\n\n5. General Medical Risks\n- Potential transmission of blood-borne pathogens\n- Potential contamination during preparation\n- Rare but possible complications from preparation process\n\n6. Adverse Physiological Reactions\n- Potential kidney complications\n- Potential coagulation disorders\n- Potential inflammatory responses\n\nMedical professionals carefully assess individual patient risks and potential benefits before administering antivenom, typically using careful screening and monitoring protocols.",
